IMF needs more Lagarde
Davos — Lagarde once said she is open to serving another five years as the International Monetary Fund (IMF)总裁.
She should remain in her position.
IMF has never had better leadership than her; the IMF Board should give her the opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, assuming leadership of an institution in crisis.
The 2008 global financial meltdown and its economic aftershocks tarnished the reputation of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free-market "Washington Consensus."
Lagarde's leadership helped restore the IMF's credibility.
Many looked to her personal qualities — as they should have.
She is candid, strong, warm, and compelling.
Officials from various countries who met with her (often in delicate circumstances) consistently remarked that she was brave in speaking the difficult truths, and also a sensitive listener.
These are important qualities for a leader of an institution that must negotiate the terms of an agreement rather than dominate everything.
Lagarde told the Europeans that their banks needed restructuring, or else they must establish firewalls to prevent financial contagion. The blunt truth was not pleasant to hear, but the Europeans followed it.
Similarly, she strongly urged providing IMF support to some countries — for example, Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine — which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not good at innovation and is usually not full of passion.
Lagarde began to change this.
During this process, she gave this often prescription-like institution a human face.
For example, helping manage the refugee crisis in the Middle East was not originally within the IMF's mandate.
However, under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plan, enabling the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to help people displaced by conflicts in Syria and Iraq (over one million people reside in refugee camps within Jordan).
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak erupted in West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF to use its available funds to provide debt relief to affected countries, allowing them to improve the treatment of doctors and nurses — this was the first time the IMF had used its own capital in such a way.
Additionally, Lagarde recognizes that the world today faces three major challenges, and she takes action on them.
First, she strongly advocates for increasing the participation of women in the workforce, and she herself serves as an example of the value of having women in leadership positions.
In various countries ranging from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urges leaders to stop wasting such a massive talent resource — and thus realize economic potential.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF also addresses the broader issue of income inequality.
This is not merely a question of basic fairness.
IMF's research emphasizes that there is a direct link between reducing income inequality and boosting economic growth.
IMF is not the first institution to prove this, but its position makes the issue more prominent and urgent.
Draghi personally has been committed to promoting this point, which is key to increasing its urgency.
Third, Draghi has played an important role in helping the world understand the full impact of technological change — some of which will cause alarming disruptive effects —
for example, automation will continue to increase the efficiency of manufacturing and reduce its costs, but also means that the number of jobs created by economic growth will be less than before.
This emerging reality's political, economic, and social consequences are worth our understanding and serious study.
Lagarde has made the IMF the core of this effort.
Critics will say it is time for representatives from developing countries to lead the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is the 11th consecutive European to hold this position, and Europe's possession of such privilege is difficult to justify in today's world.
Some also argue that the IMF's support for Greece's austerity measures has not yielded significant results, proving she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some people will point out that she faces charges related to financial scandals in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn was embroiled in a scandal, critics believe the IMF cannot again be distracted by similar incidents.
We will analyze these objections one by one.
The IMF (and the World Bank) should welcome leaders from outside of Europe and the United States.
But the purpose of ending this Western privilege is to base the leader selection process on merit rather than political considerations.
Lagarde is the best choice to be the IMF's Managing Director, and emerging powers such as the BRICS countries (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) did not jointly nominate an alternative candidate.
Having an European serve as the IMF's Managing Director might also have been one of the favorable factors behind the IMF's decision last year to include the RMB in the basket of currencies that determine the value of the Special Drawing Rights.
Additionally, Lagarde, with her impressive political flexibility, ultimately persuaded both the Republican and Democratic parties in the U.S. Congress to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only enhanced the IMF's arsenal against financial crises but also more accurately reflected the changing dynamics of the global economy.
For example, the BRICS countries are now among the top ten shareholders of the IMF.
On the issue of Greece, Lagarde made some notably personal and direct — some might say inappropriate — comments last year.
But she is not the culprit who brought economic pain to the Greeks. Her tenure at the IMF fully demonstrated that no IMF Managing Director in its history has done so much to lead the IMF in alleviating the suffering of people during crises as she has.
Finally, the French prosecutors opposed the accusations against Lagarde, and she was at most only slightly involved.
The world urgently needs a leader committed to making the world safer and more prosperous.
Lagarde has shown that she is exactly such a leader, committed to adapting the IMF for the twenty-first century.
She deserves the opportunity to see her work through to the end.
